<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">
Gregarious worms commonly known as &quot;honey comb worms&quot;. Tubes constructed with sea shells fragments, echinoderm spines debris, sand and small gravel (as well as 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. cretus" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" rank="species" species="cretus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">I. cretus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Complete specimens 8-11.1 mm long, 1-2 mm wide, with 27-30 abdominal chaetigers and a caudal peduncle 2-3 mm long. Body divided into four specialised regions: operculum, parathorax (with three segments), abdomen and caudal region (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
A). Operculum composed by a crown and a peduncle, forming two not fused lobes. Median organ short, not longer than opercular lobes. Outer palea with straight blades; base of blades with transversal thecal fringes (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
E), lateral denticles straight (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
F), longer and narrower towards tips (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
G). Inner paleae straight with markedly, transversal thecae and pointed tips (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
H-J). A pair of nuchal hooks curved (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
B) without hoods or limbations on concave sides of hooks (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
C). Abdominal uncini with six pairs of teeth in side view (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
D).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">
This constitutes the fist record since its establishment by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kirtley, D. W." journalOrPublisher="Sabecon Press, Scientific Series Florida, Florida" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" refId="B5999853" refString="Kirtley, D. W., 1994. A review and taxonomic revision of the Family Sabellariidae Johnston, 1865 (Annelida; Polychaeta. Sabecon Press, Scientific Series Florida, Florida" title="A review and taxonomic revision of the Family Sabellariidae Johnston, 1865 (Annelida; Polychaeta" year="1994">Kirtley (1994)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">
This species was described from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bahía">Bahia</normalizedToken>
Tenacatita, west of the islets off Barra de Navidad, between 45.7 and 64 m depth. A second species from Western Mexico is 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fauchald" authorityYear="1972" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellariidae" genus="Idanthyrsus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Idanthyrsus armatopsis" order="Sabellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="armatopsis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">Idanthyrsus armatopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fauchald, 1972 
<bibRefCitation author="Fauchald, K" journalOrPublisher="Allan Hancock Monographs Marine Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" pagination="1 - 575" refId="B5999559" refString="Fauchald, K, 1972. Benthic polychaetous annelids from deep waters off Western Mexico and adjacent areas in the Eastern Pacific Ocean. Allan Hancock Monographs Marine Biology 7: 1 - 575" title="Benthic polychaetous annelids from deep waters off Western Mexico and adjacent areas in the Eastern Pacific Ocean" volume="7" year="1972">Fauchald (1972)</bibRefCitation>
described from bathyal depths (1200 -1400 m) in the Gulf of California. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirtley" authorityYear="1994" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellariidae" genus="Idanthyrsus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Idanthyrsus mexicanus" order="Sabellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">Idanthyrsus mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. armatopsis" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" rank="species" species="armatopsis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">I. armatopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares the presence of nuchal hooks without hoods, but the inner paleae in 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. mexicanus" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">I. mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have pointed tips versus blunt tips in 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. armatopsis." pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" rank="species" species="armatopsis.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">I. armatopsis.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Number of teeth of abdominal uncini was not described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kirtley, D. W." journalOrPublisher="Sabecon Press, Scientific Series Florida, Florida" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" refId="B5999853" refString="Kirtley, D. W., 1994. A review and taxonomic revision of the Family Sabellariidae Johnston, 1865 (Annelida; Polychaeta. Sabecon Press, Scientific Series Florida, Florida" title="A review and taxonomic revision of the Family Sabellariidae Johnston, 1865 (Annelida; Polychaeta" year="1994">Kirtley (1994)</bibRefCitation>
to 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. mexicanus" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">I. mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but specimens here reported from Chamela Bay have six teeth in side view versus 7-8 teeth in 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. armatopsis" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" rank="species" species="armatopsis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">I. armatopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The median organ in 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. mexicanus" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">I. mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(not described in original description by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kirtley, D. W." journalOrPublisher="Sabecon Press, Scientific Series Florida, Florida" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" refId="B5999853" refString="Kirtley, D. W., 1994. A review and taxonomic revision of the Family Sabellariidae Johnston, 1865 (Annelida; Polychaeta. Sabecon Press, Scientific Series Florida, Florida" title="A review and taxonomic revision of the Family Sabellariidae Johnston, 1865 (Annelida; Polychaeta" year="1994">Kirtley 1994</bibRefCitation>
) is short, extending only 1/4 above lateral opercular lobes, whereas in 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. armatopsis" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" rank="species" species="armatopsis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">I. armatopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this organ extends 1/2 above lateral opercular lobes.
</paragraph>
